\c 10
\iex 1 Sauls ouerthrow and death. 8 The Philistines triumph ouer Saul. 11 The kindnes of Iabesh Gilead, towards Saul and his sonnes. 13 Sauls sinne for which the kingdome was translated from him to Dauid.
\v 1 ¶ Nowe \x + \xo 10:1 \xt 1.Sam. 31.1,2.\x*the Philistines fought against Israel, and the men of Israel fled from before the Philistines, and fell downe \f + \fr 10:1 \ft Or, wounded.\f*slaine in mount Gilboa.
\v 2 And the Philistines followed hard after Saul, and after his sonnes, and the Philistines slew Ionathan, and \f + \fr 10:2 \ft Or, Ieshui, \xt 1.Sam. 14.49.\f*Abinadab, and Malchishua, the sonnes of Saul.
\v 3 And the battell went sore against Saul, and the \f + \fr 10:3 \ft Hebr. shooters with bowes.\f*archers \f + \fr 10:3 \ft Hebr. found him.\f*hit him, and he was wounded of the archers.
\v 4 Then saide Saul to his armour bearer, Draw thy sword, and thrust me through therewith, lest these vncircumcised come, and \f + \fr 10:4 \ft Or, mocke me.\f*abuse mee: but his armour bearer would not, for he was sore afraid. So Saul tooke a sword, and fell vpon it.
\v 5 And when his armour bearer saw that Saul was dead, hee fell likewise on the sword, and died.
\v 6 So Saul died, and his three sonnes, and all his house died together.
\v 7 And when all the men of Israel that \add were\add* in the valley, saw that they fled, and that Saul and his sonnes were dead: then they forsooke their cities, and fled, and the Philistines came and dwelt in them.
\v 8 ¶ And it came to passe on the morrow, when the Philistines came to strip the slaine, that they found Saul and his sonnes fallen in mount Gilboa.
\v 9 And when they had stripped him, they tooke his head, and his armour, and sent into the land of the Philistines round about, to cary tidings vnto their idoles, and to the people.
\v 10 And they put his armour in the house of their gods, and fastened his head in the temple of Dagon.
\v 11 ¶ And when all Iabesh Gilead heard all that the Philistines had done to Saul:
\v 12 They arose, all the valiant men, and tooke away the body of Saul, and the bodies of his sonnes, and brought them to Iabesh, and buried their bones vnder the oke in Iabesh, and fasted seuen dayes.
\v 13 ¶ So Saul died for his transgression which hee \f + \fr 10:13 \ft Heb. transgressed.\f*committed against the \nd LORD\nd*, \x + \xo 10:13 \xt 1.Sam. 15.23.\x*\add euen\add* against the word of the \nd LORD\nd* which he kept not, and also for asking \add counsel\add* of \add one that had\add* a familiar spirit, \x + \xo 10:13 \xt 1.Sam. 28.7.\x*to enquire \add of it\add*:
\v 14 And enquired not of the \nd LORD\nd*: therefore he slew him, and turned the kingdome vnto Dauid the sonne of \f + \fr 10:14 \ft Heb. Isai.\f*Iesse.
\c 11
\iex 1 Dauid by a generall consent is made king at Hebron. 4 Hee winneth the castle of Sion from the Iebusites, by Ioabs valour. 10 A catalogue of Dauids mightie men.
\v 1 ¶ Then \x + \xo 11:1 \xt 2.Sam. 5.\x*all Israel gathered themselues to Dauid vnHebron, saying, Behold, wee \add are\add* thy bone and thy flesh.
\v 2 And moreouer \f + \fr 11:2 \ft Heb. both yesterday and the third day.\f*in time past, euen when Saul was king, thou \add wast\add* he that leddest out and broughtest in Israel: and the \nd LORD\nd* thy God said vnto thee, Thou shalt \f + \fr 11:2 \ft Or, rule.\f*feede my people Israel, and thou shalt be ruler ouer my people Israel.
\v 3 Therefore came all the Elders of Israel to the king to Hebron, and Dauid made a couenant with them in Hebron before the \nd LORD\nd*, and they annointed Dauid king ouer Israel, according to the word of the \nd LORD\nd*, \f + \fr 11:3 \ft Heb. by the hand of.\f*by \x + \xo 11:3 \xt 1 Sam. 16.13.\x*Samuel.
\v 4 ¶ And Dauid & all Israel, \x + \xo 11:4 \xt 2 Sam. 5.6.\x*went to Ierusalem, which \add is\add* Iebus, where the Iebusites \add were\add* the inhabitants of the land.
\v 5 And the inhabitants of Iebus said to Dauid, Thou shalt not come hither. Neuerthelesse Dauid tooke the castle of Zion, which \add is\add* the citie of Dauid.
\v 6 And Dauid said, Whosoeuer smiteth the Iebusites first, shall be \f + \fr 11:6 \ft Heb, head.\f*chiefe, and captaine. So Ioab the sonne of Zeruiah went first vp, and was chiefe.
\v 7 And Dauid dwelt in the castell: therefore they called \f + \fr 11:7 \ft That is, Zion, \xt 2.Sam 5.7.\f*it the citie of Dauid.
\v 8 And he built the citie round about, euen from Millo round about: and Ioab \f + \fr 11:8 \ft Heb. reuiued.\f*repaired the rest of the citie.
\v 9 So Dauid \f + \fr 11:9 \ft Heb. went in going and increasing.\f*waxed greater and greater: for the \nd LORD\nd* of hostes \add was\add* with him.
\v 10 ¶ \x + \xo 11:10 \xt 2.Sam. 23.8.\x*These also \add are\add* the chiefe of the mightie men, whom Dauid had, who \f + \fr 11:10 \ft Or, held strongly with him.\f*strenthened themselues with him in his kingdome, \add and\add* with all Israel, to make him king according to the word of the \nd LORD\nd*, concerning Israel.
\v 11 And this \add is\add* the number of the mightie men, whom Dauid had: Iashobeam \f + \fr 11:11 \ft Or, Sonne of Hachmoni.\f*an Hachmonite, the chiefe of the captaines: he lift vp his speare against three hundred, slaine \add by him\add* at one time.
\v 12 And after him \add was\add* Eleazar the sonne of Dodo the Ahohite, who \add was one\add* of the three mighties.
\v 13 He was with Dauid at \f + \fr 11:13 \ft Or, Ephesdammim, \xt 1.Sam. 17.1.\f*Pasdammim; and there the Philistines were gathered together to battell, where was a parcell of ground full of barley, and the people fled from before the Philistines.
\v 14 And they \f + \fr 11:14 \ft Or, stood.\f*set themselues in the middest of \add that\add* parcell, and deliuered it, and slue the \x + \xo 11:14 \xt 2.Sam. 23.13.\x*Philistines, & the \nd LORD\nd* saued \add them\add* by a great \f + \fr 11:14 \ft Or, saluation.\f*deliuerance.
\v 15 ¶ Now \f + \fr 11:15 \ft Or, three captaines ouer the thirtie.\f*three of the thirtie captaines, went downe to the rocke of Dauid, into the caue of Adullam, and the host of the Philistines encamped in the valley of Rephaim.
\v 16 And Dauid \add was\add* then in the hold, and the Philistines garison \add was\add* then at Bethlehem.
\v 17 And Dauid longed and said, Oh that one would giue me drinke of the water of the well of Bethlehem, that \add is\add* at the gate.
\v 18 And the three brake through the host of the Philistines, and drew water out of the well of Bethlehem, that \add was\add* by the gate, and tooke \add it\add* and brought \add it\add* to Dauid. But Dauid would not drink \add of\add* it, but powred it out to the \nd LORD\nd*,
\v 19 And said, My God forbid it mee, that I should doe this thing. Shall I drinke the blood of these men, \f + \fr 11:19 \ft Heb. with their liues?\f*that haue put their liues in ieopardie? for with the ieopardie of their liues, they brought it: therfore he would not drink it. These things did these three mightiest.
\v 20 ¶ And Abishai the brother of Ioab, he was chiefe of the three. For lifting vp his speare against three hundred, he slew \add them\add*, and had a name among the three.
\v 21 \x + \xo 11:21 \xt 2.Sam. 23.19. &c.\x*Of the three, hee was more honourable then the two, for he was their captaine; howbeit, he attained not to the \add first\add* three.
\v 22 Benaiah the sonne of Iehoiada, the sonne of a valiant man of Kabzeel, \f + \fr 11:22 \ft Heb. great of deeds.\f*who had done many acts: he slue two Lyon-like men of Moab, also he went downe and slue a Lyon in a pit in a snowy day.
\v 23 And he slue an Egyptian, \f + \fr 11:23 \ft Heb. a man of measure.\f*a man of \add great\add* stature, fiue cubits high, and in the Egyptians hand \add was\add* a speare like a weauers beame: and he went downe to him with a staffe, and pluckt the speare out of the Egyptians hand, and slue him with his owne speare.
\v 24 These \add things\add* did Benaiah the sonne of Iehoiada, and had the name among the three mighties.
\v 25 Behold, hee was honourable among the thirtie, but attained not to the \add first\add* three: and Dauid set him ouer his guard.
